    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="Razer Kishi" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/wm-rnZckZ7fUXyXuwWihYRFo2YE=/0x85:2040x1445/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/69421938/cfaulkner_200604_4054_0006.0.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;&lt;em&gt;It can fit almost any Android phone, aside from the Galaxy S20 Ultra.&lt;/em&gt; | Photo by Cameron Faulkner / The Verge&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="KV7TDO"&gt;The Razer Kishi is one of the &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/21285073/razer-kishi-review-game-controller-phone-price-nintendo-switch-stadia"&gt;best mobile controllers out there&lt;/a&gt;, and you can get it for significantly less than it usually costs at &lt;a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B086X8DHN2?tag=theverge02-20" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener" target="_blank"&gt;Amazon&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="https://shop-links.co/1742848825048987882#donotlink" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener" target="_blank"&gt;Best Buy&lt;/a&gt;. Normally $80, the version of the controller made for Android costs $55. The Kishi is compact, yet it can expand to fit most phones (excluding the Samsung Galaxy S20 Ultra). It features passthrough USB-C charging, and its overall design looks like a Nintendo Switch, but people who are used to gaming on an Xbox Series X controller should feel at home with the feel and arrangement of the Kishi’s buttons, sticks and triggers.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id="fYS9lr"&gt;&lt;div data-anthem-component="productcard:10228224"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
